2026-04-16 12:11:28 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['cable connection between power supply module and control module (both conductors)'] hypothesis_explanation='The power-supply output leads are cross-connected to the control-module input leads: PSU +12 V is tied to the control-module 0 V node and PSU 0 V is tied to the control-module +12 V node. This exactly matches the observation: the control-module ‘inverted cables’ LED is designed to light only when its own + and − rails are reversed with respect to the upstream supply, yet the power-supply indicator LED is still on, confirming that the PSU itself is correctly powered. With the control rails reversed, the series switch and the downstream load/diode network never see correct polarity, so the lamp does not illuminate even when the switch is closed. The observed wiring between control and load is correct, so the sole configuration fault is the polarity-swapped pair of conductors between the power-supply cube and the control cube. Reconnecting those two conductors so that PSU + goes to control + and PSU − goes to control − should restore normal lamp operation and extinguish the red ‘inverted cables’ LED.'
